I've only used awk a little, but it comes in handy!

Simple example:

    ls data/sql/ | awk '{ print $1}'

More complicated:

    awk '/map:query src=/ { print $1 }' RS="sql/|\"/>" config/sitemap.xml | sort

Usage with xargs and [[subversion]]:

    svn st | awk '{ print $2 }' | xargs svn add

#### Example of Awk and XML
In my humble opinion, awk is the grand bridge capable of bringing command line data to the web, via [[XML]] and [[XSL]]. Here's an example:

    #!/bin/sh
    echo "&lt;ps>" > /tmp/ps.xml && ps -A | awk '{print "&lt;proc>&lt;pid>"$1"&lt;/pid>&lt;tty>"$2"&lt;/tty>&lt;time>"$3"&lt;/time>&lt;command>"$4"&lt;/command>&lt;/proc>"}' >> /tmp/ps.xml && echo "&lt;/ps>" >> /tmp/ps.xml

#### Another Random Example

    #!/bin/sh
    cp $1 /tmp/tmp.bk
    grep '#ZZ\*' $1 > /dev/null
    
    if [ "$?" -ne "0" ]
    then
    echo "commenting it out"
    cat $1 | awk '
    /#ZZ$/ { printf "%s", $0; next }
    {print}
    ' > /tmp/tmp.tmp
    else
        echo "freeing it up"
        sed 's/#ZZ\*/#ZZ\n\*/g' $1   > /tmp/tmp.tmp
    fi
    mv /tmp/tmp.tmp $1
    exit 0

